<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-14T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-14T05:00:00-05:00" n="351" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/4186: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="from">Cunningham</persName>) to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-14T18:00:00+08:00">February 14, 1932—6
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received February 14—10:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>50. Continuing my daily report number 45 of February 13, 4 p.m.</p>
                        <p>1. In keeping with the day the situation[s] along both the Chapei and
                            Woosung fronts have remained comparatively quiet. Twelve thousand
                            Japanese troops reported to have landed at the N.Y.K. Wayside Wharf in
                            the International Settlement.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Legation, repeated to Nanking.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CES1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>